{
  "text": "Another interesting result to be shown here is the instantaneous error signal, j \u03b5 . Fig. 19 shows various cases for the sampled version of this signal after running the proposed model three times for three values of the learning speed \u03bc . The results justify the mathematical proof in [CITATION_1] which is given by equation (9) and states that if \u03bc is chosen to be 0.5, the output of the adaptive LMS spectrum analyzer will be equal to the DFT of the input sampled signal at the previous time instance. Otherwise, j \u03b5 will never reach zero as the case shows in Fig. 19 (a) . Fig. 19 (c) shows that when \u03bc is chosen to be more than 1, j \u03b5 is increasing up to infinity as the LMS algorithm becomes unstable. ",
  "citation_candidates": [
